      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person sex="1">
               <persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth"> ያዕቆብ፡ </persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Yāʿǝqob </persName>
               <persName><roleName type="title">ʾabuna</roleName></persName>
               <occupation type="ecclesiastic"> metropolitan </occupation>
               <nationality type="Egypt"/>
               <faith type="Coptic"/>
             
               <floruit>  He was a 14th century metropolitan of the Ethiopian Orthodox Church who arrived in <date> 1337</date> during the reign of 
                  <persName ref="PRS1854Amdase">ʾAmda Ṣǝyon I</persName>. He was the successor of ʾabuna <persName ref="PRS10391Yohanne"> Yoḥannǝs II </persName>.  
                  His name appears in five hagiographies of the medieval saints including <title ref="LIT1428GadlaB">Gadla Baṣalota Mikāʾel</title>, 
                  <title ref="LIT1445GadlaF">Gadla Filǝṗṗos (za-Dabra Libānos)</title>,<title ref="LIT1420GadlaA">Gadla ʾAnorewos </title>,
                  <title ref="LIT1423GadlaA">Gadla ʾAron (za-Dabra Dāret)</title> and <title ref="LIT1496GadlaS">Gadla Sāmuʾel (Dabra Wagag)</title>. 
                  He devoted  together with some of the leaders of the local monasticism to evangelize non-chrisitian regions of <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa">Šawā</placeName>, <placeName ref="LOC3061Fataga">Faṭagār</placeName>, 
                  <placeName ref="LOC6136Waj">Waǧ</placeName>,<placeName ref="LOC2488Damot">Dāmot</placeName>, <placeName ref="LOC2966Ennary">Ǝnnāryā</placeName> and  
                  <placeName ref="LOC3921Ifat">Ifāt</placeName>. He was in conflict with King  <persName ref="PRS1854Amdase">ʾAmda Ṣǝyon I</persName> because 
                 of  his marriage with the wife of his father. Finally, he was expelled to Egypt in around <date>1345</date>.
                 </floruit>
